1385,IssuesEvent,2018-06-22 18:48:47+00:00,913279,tkrajina/gpxpy,379243,tkrajina,,,closed,exact distance?!?,[],[],2,"I try to generate some gpx files for unittests...

To keep it simple, here's what I'm gonna do:

- use the circumference of the equator. This is 40075.017 kilometres (WGS 84)
- generate GPX data with `latitude=0` and `elevation=0`
- iterate the longitude based on the track length and `40075.017km / 360°`

Based on this i made a function to generate a GPX file and compare the distance... But i have some differences...

I generate a 10km long GPX tracks and get this:

```
real length...: 10000.0 m
gpxpy length..: 9982.1 m
Diff..........: 17.9 m
```

I generate a track that is ""half the length of the earth equator"" long and get this:

```
real length...: 20037.5 km
gpxpy length..: 20015.1 km
Diff..........: 22.4 km
```
The generates GPX looks like this:
```
<trkpt lat=""0"" lon=""0"">...</trkpt>
<trkpt lat=""0"" lon=""1.0"">...</trkpt>
<trkpt lat=""0"" lon=""2.0"">...</trkpt>
...
<trkpt lat=""0"" lon=""179.0"">...</trkpt>
<trkpt lat=""0"" lon=""180.0"">...</trkpt>
```

The full sources + the two gpx files are in gist, here:
- **test_gpx.py** -> https://gist.github.com/jedie/e86b3fc415e01e343bdecd8303c0d722#file-test_gpx-py
- **generated_10km.gpx** -> https://gist.github.com/jedie/e86b3fc415e01e343bdecd8303c0d722#file-generated_10km-gpx
- **half_equator.gpx** -> https://gist.github.com/jedie/e86b3fc415e01e343bdecd8303c0d722#file-half_equator-gpx

I also patch `gpxpy.geo.distance` and force to use and not use `gpxpy.geo.haversine_distance` but this doesn't really matter...

So i think my generation of longitude is simply wrong?!?
Any idea where i can get gpx test data with exact information about the content?

EDIT: Hm. I found https://www.j-berkemeier.de/ShowGPX.html and upload the generated GPX files. The distances there is exact the same as my ""real length"", e.g. from **half_equator.gpx**

![grafik](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/71315/41610624-03239232-73ee-11e8-984e-f21eb90c4dc8.png)

So have i found a bug in gpxpy?!?",{},{}
1386,IssuesEvent,2017-01-07 06:30:38+00:00,913279,tkrajina/gpxpy,3864333,stac47,,,opened,gpxpy writes logs in the root logger,[],[],0,"Hello,

I spotted that throughout the library, the logs are written in the ROOT logger. This is not really convenient if an application using this library wants to redirect the logs to another file.

I would propose to define a default logger for the gpxpy library and prevent writing logs by default as explained here https://docs.python.org/3/howto/logging.html#library-config.

If you think it is worth taking some time to do it, just tell me and I will provide a PR.
Regards,
Stac",{},{}
1427,IssuesEvent,2017-10-02 17:16:44+00:00,68290807,Stewori/pytypes,585279,mitar,,,opened,README.rst contains utf-8 characters,[],[],0,"So this means package cannot be installed on systems which do not have current local set to utf-8. In Python 3, you get an error like:

```
UnicodeDecodeError: 'ascii' codec can't decode byte 0xe2 in position 8634: ordinal not in range(128)
```

One option would be to do `open(readme_path, encoding='utf8').read()`, but this would not work on Python 2, where you will have to use `io.open`.

Other is that you remove all unicode characters from the README.",{},{}
