3961,IssuesEvent,2016-04-16 14:19:11+00:00,7433211,jmcnamara/XlsxWriter,94267,jmcnamara,,,closed,Documentation Conflict re: workbook.close(),"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/jmcnamara/XlsxWriter/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/jmcnamara/XlsxWriter/labels/documentation', 'name': 'documentation', 'color': '009800'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/jmcnamara/XlsxWriter/labels/short%20term', 'name': 'short term', 'color': '009800'}]",[],2,"Hi,

I am reporting a conflict in documentation regarding the workbook.close(). The ""Tutorial 1"" section states that workbook.close() is optional while ""The Workbook Class"" section states that workbook.close() is mandatory.

Suggested fix - delete the following from Tutorial 1:

```
Like most file objects in Python an XlsxWriter file is closed implicitly when it goes out of scope or
is no longer referenced in the program. As such this line is generally optional unless you need to
close the file explicitly.
```

Background:

In the PDF dated January 16, 2016 (the April 11 2016 PDF build is malformed at only 19 pages), and consistent across with the HTML at http://xlsxwriter.readthedocs.org/tutorial01.html , page 11 states:

```
Like most file objects in Python an XlsxWriter file is closed implicitly when it goes out of scope or
is no longer referenced in the program. As such this line is generally optional unless you need to
close the file explicitly.
```
In particular, the second sentence states the line is generally optional.

However page 27 of the same PDF states:

```
The workbook close() method writes all data to the xlsx file and closes it. This is a mandatory
method call:
workbook.close()
Note: Earlier versions of XlsxWriter allowed an implicit close() that was triggered by the
garbage collector. However, this proved to be too problematic and non-deterministic. An explicit
close() is now recommended in all XlsxWriter programs.
```
In particular, the second sentence of the first paragraph indicates that the call is mandatory not the optional described in the Tutorial.",{},{}
3963,IssuesEvent,2016-03-21 10:07:48+00:00,7433211,jmcnamara/XlsxWriter,94267,jmcnamara,,,closed,ISSUE with set_row format and columns with dates,[],[],2,"Hi,

I am using XlsxWriter to do write a pandas dataframe and change the background color of rows but it appears to NOT change background color of the column with datetime data.  All other columns in the rows that I have set a color format are properly colored.

I am using Python version 2.7.6 and XlsxWriter 0.8.4 and Excel version 2013, pandas 0.17.1
![2016-03-05 13_45_34-test xlsx - excel](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/11460139/13550707/a146ff20-e2d8-11e5-8859-b298173b76a9.png)
[test.xlsx](https://github.com/jmcnamara/XlsxWriter/files/160055/test.xlsx)



Here is some code that demonstrates the problem:

```python
import os
import pandas as pd
path = r'.'
xlsfname = 'test.xlsx'

df = pd.DataFrame({'date' :pd.date_range('01/05/2016','01/10/2016'),
                    'data': pd.Series(1,index=list(range(6)),dtype='float32')                   
                   })
writer = pd.ExcelWriter(os.path.join(path,xlsfname), engine='xlsxwriter')
df.to_excel(writer,'wip',index=False)
workbook = writer.book
wipWKS = writer.sheets['wip']
#set up format for highlighted rows
hform1 = workbook.add_format()
hform1.set_pattern(1)
hform1.set_bg_color('#DDD9C4') # dark tan
wipWKS.set_column('B:B',18)
wipWKS.set_row(3,None,hform1)
workbook.close()


```

",{},{}
