6554,IssuesEvent,2018-02-02 09:05:15+00:00,3678981,sripathikrishnan/redis-rdb-tools,991744,sripathikrishnan,,,opened,Discussion: Improving performance of memory analyzer,[],[],0,"I spent the last few days trying to optimize the performance of memory analyzer. At this point, I wanted to start a discussion on the results, and how we can merge it back into the redis-rdb-tools.

Creating test RDB files
-----
I first needed a set of rdb files to work against. Synthetic rdb files, those generated from redis-benchmark didn't cover all patterns. So I made a set of RDB files from real world data. See 

1. [Importing StackExchange Archives into Redis](https://gist.github.com/sripathikrishnan/df4d91580da60b2032916ac2a172bae4)
2. [Import US H1B applications to Redis](https://gist.github.com/sripathikrishnan/88284aa75dc30fc650d1553233561e2c)

For benchmarking, I created askubuntu.rdb file using the stackexchange script. This has about 3.6M keys. Using the unstable version of redis-rdb-tools, generating the memory csv took about 18 minutes on my laptop. This was with python-lzf installed.

(Trying to) Improve Python Code
-----
Looking at the python code, I realized a few things - 
1. To calculate the memory, we don't actually need to load the entire object from the RDB. For example, for strings, just knowing the length of the string and whether it is a numeric value is enough to calculate the memory. 
1. The RdbCallback interface is a big overhead. It is a good interface for other things like JSON conversion where we need all the keys and values, but for memory calculations it's a poor abstraction.
1. The python code itself isn't written in a IO performant manner. 

To address these concerns, I rewrote the memory analyzer in a new python module called indexer.py. With these changes, the CSV generation took about 9 minutes for askubuntu.rdb.

This wasn't good enough, so I tried to profile the python code. It seems we are generating too many objects, and that the IO is not buffered inspite of all my attempts to get it to buffer. I have a few ideas on how to tackle the object creation, but I haven't got on to that yet. 

I paused the efforts, and decided to try something else.

Rewriting in C
-----
I wondered what the performance would be like if this was written in C. So I started hacking, and wrote a version that just printed the keys. To my surprise, the program ran successfully in just about 9 seconds! That was a massive improvement, so I started adding all the features. 

At this point, I have a 80% working C version. I have also been successful in calling this C function from python, so we can introduce the C code without breaking the current python CLI interface. 

Next Steps / Discussion Items
-----
1. I am hoping to complete the C version, integrate it with the python CLI, and ensure all the existing bugs are fixed. For example, proper quoting of key names, proper escaping of characters in the key, revisit the memory calculation. Do you see any specific concerns, or are there specific implementation bugs I should address while I am re-writing it in C?
2. I am thinking of dropping support for 32 bit version of redis in the memory calculation. In other words, I am assuming 64 bit redis is used. Do you see a problem with this? 
3. I am introducing a new field in the CSV - ""savingsIfCompressed"". Since the values are compressed in the rdb but are not compressed in memory - if we were to simply compute ( length - compressed length), we would get a decent idea if it's worth compressing the value pair before saving it in Redis. 
4. I am planning to convert the newly added expiry timestamp to a relative timestamp. Meaning, instead of ""key expires at this time"", say ""key expires in 4 hours"". This makes the memory analysis independent of current time. The RDB file already has the creation time in an aux field, so the calculation is easy. In case the aux field is not available, rdb generation time can be found out 1) using file creation time, 2) finding the least expiry time, 3) asking the user. 
5. The current CSV has a column lengthOfLargestElement. This was added so that users can tweak the *-ziplist-* configurations. This value is easy enough to compute for certain encodings like hashtable, set, skiplist and so, but is expensive for embedded encodings like quicklist, ziplist etc. This is because we have to first uncompress the entire string, and then traverse each element to find the largest element. For hashtables, skiplists etc, the elements are stored as strings with their length prefixed, so we don't have to load the entire string. But the realization is that if rdb is already using an embedded encoding, it is already memory optimized, and we know the lengthOfLargestElement is less than 512 anyways. So - my thought was to only find this value for un-optimized encodings like hashtable/skiplist, and ignore it for embedded encodings. Do you agree with this decision?

P.S. 
The source code is in the perf branch over here https://github.com/hashedin/redis-rdb-tools. The code is neither feature complete nor is it written well enough for me to open a pull request. But hopefully I can get some early feedback. 

 Specifically, two files should be of interest - 
1. [rdbtools.c](https://github.com/hashedin/redis-rdb-tools/blob/perf/native/rdbtools.c) the hacked C version of the code.
1. [indexer.py](https://github.com/hashedin/redis-rdb-tools/blob/perf/rdbtools/indexer.py) - the faster version of the current memory parser. 

",{},{}
