10011,IssuesEvent,2017-04-06 10:02:08+00:00,3342046,RDFLib/rdflib,715019,RinkeHoekstra,1401847,RDFLib,opened,The N-triple serializer incorrectly encodes URIs and Literals,[],[],0,"N-triple serializers incorrectly encode URIs and Literals in the object position.

For instance, a URIRef `http://data.socialhistory.org/resource/hisco/DDB1/packmästare` as subject, predicate and object is rendered as:

`<http://data.socialhistory.org/resource/hisco/DDB1/packm\u00E4stare> <http://data.socialhistory.org/resource/hisco/DDB1/packm\u00E4stare> <http://data.socialhistory.org/resource/hisco/DDB1/packm\u00E4stare>`

A literal has the same issue. As of RDFLib v4.2.2 this works fine for NQuads (in 4.2.1 both NQuads and N-Triples incorrectly encoded URIs in the object position). Turtle serialiser works fine in both versions.

To replicate:

```
from rdflib import Dataset, URIRef, Literal

uri = u""http://data.socialhistory.org/resource/hisco/DDB1/packmästare""
literal = u""packmästare""

g = Dataset()

s = URIRef(uri)
p = URIRef(uri)
o = URIRef(uri)
l = Literal(literal)

g.add((s,p,o))
g.add((s,p,l))

with open(""encoding-test.nq"",'w') as f:
    g.serialize(f, format='nquads')
    
with open(""encoding-test.nt"",'w') as f:
    g.serialize(f, format='nt')
    
with open(""encoding-test.ttl"",'w') as f:
    g.serialize(f, format='turtle')
```",{},{}
10016,IssuesEvent,2018-06-14 12:05:35+00:00,83748372,h2oai/datatable,7123439,chrinide,1402695,h2oai,opened,How about Windows support? Win7 & Win10 ,[],[],0,How about Windows support? Win7 & Win10 ,{},{}
10082,IssuesEvent,2016-01-06 04:33:02+00:00,3510804,GalSim-developers/GalSim,623887,rmjarvis,1462196,GalSim-developers,opened,"Make Ring a stamp type, not a gal type",[],[],0,"Now that I've introduced `stamp` as a new top-level config field in #691, I've been thinking that our 'Ring' galaxy type really ought to be a stamp type.  I think it makes more logical sense, but since it is an API change, I figured I should raise the idea as an issue before implementing it to see if anyone had comments about it.

The new syntax I'm proposing for demo5 say is:
````
stamp:
    type: Ring
    num: 2

    # Put the transformations to do after the Ring rotation here:
    shear :
        type : G1G2
        g1 : 0.013
        g2 : -0.008

    shift :
        type : RandomCircle
        radius : 1 # arcsec

gal :
    type : Exponential
    resolution : 0.98

    # Only include the transformation that happen for the first galaxy in the ring, prior to the ring rotation.
    ellip :
        ...
```

It seems like this is a bit more logical than having Ring be the ""galaxy type"".  That never really matched the concept we had for all the other galaxy types very well.  But since I hadn't thought of the stamp type yet, there wasn't really a better place for it.  But now I think there is.

Thoughts?  

If we do this, I'd like to actually deprecate the Ring galaxy type, so it would be backwards compatible for now, but it would give a warning.  Unlike the other changes I've made recently to the config stuff that were all expansions in functionality and are fully backwards compatible.",{},{}
10091,IssuesEvent,2016-06-21 00:12:05+00:00,3510804,GalSim-developers/GalSim,3650485,jmeyers314,1462196,GalSim-developers,opened,boost 1.60 shared_ptr registration,[],[],0,"I encountered the error 

```
TypeError: No to_python (by-value) converter found for C++ type: boost::shared_ptr<galsim::GSParams>
```

in dozens of unit tests when switching from boost 1.59.5 to boost 1.60.0.  This appears to be related to a change in the way the GSParams shared_ptr gets registered.  Inserting the following line at then end of `PyGSParams::wrap` solves the issue under boost 1.60:

```
            bp::register_ptr_to_python< boost::shared_ptr<GSParams> >();
```

but then I start getting the following warning (at least it's not an error!) back under boost 1.59.5:

```
RuntimeWarning: to-Python converter for boost::shared_ptr<galsim::GSParams> already registered; second conversion method ignored.
```

So probably there's a more elegant solution...",{},{}
10095,IssuesEvent,2015-11-17 02:40:44+00:00,3510804,GalSim-developers/GalSim,1454906,rmandelb,1462196,GalSim-developers,opened,let InterpolatedImage read in an image from a multi-extension fits file?,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/GalSim-developers/GalSim/labels/feature%20request', 'name': 'feature request', 'color': 'd4c5f9'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/GalSim-developers/GalSim/labels/input/output', 'name': 'input/output', 'color': 'e10c02'}]",[],0,"This issue was inspired by a conversation with @TallJimbo .

Currently, InterpolatedImage can take an image or a string representing the filename for a FITS file with the image.  I think it would be useful if InterpolatedImage (both the python and config interface) could be given a multi-extension FITS file with some way to specify which of the images it should take.  At first I thought this must already be possible because of ```RealGalaxy``` but then I realized that functionality is all hidden inside the ```RealGalaxyCatalog``` class (```getGal``` method) and not accessible in other contexts.

At the python level, I think we want to avoid having yet another kwarg.  One option would be to make three options (instead of two) for ```image```: an image, a string for the filename, or a tuple/list that will be interpreted as ```(filename, extension)```.

For config, we could perhaps include it in the string that is used to specify the filename, e.g., check if the filename has anything after the "".fits"", and whatever it is tells the extension?  So ""myfile.fits.37"" would mean to use the 37th extension of ""myfile.fits""?  I don't love this - other ideas?  I feel like I'm missing some obvious option.

I think this is something I could code up fairly quickly myself, but would like some feedback on the above suggestions first.",{},{}
10123,IssuesEvent,2016-02-19 13:36:41+00:00,34906350,BlueBrain/NeuroM,15011025,eleftherioszisis,1479142,BlueBrain,opened,Glial cell cross section representation,[],[],0,"Currently, node cross section is assumed to be a circle, which does not convey enough information in order to represent glial cells.

According to Dan it would be sufficient if we could add one more parameter in the value array for each node which will reflect the real perimeter of the cell which will be imported from the file. The area of the cross section can be represented by a circle with equivalent area.

To summarize an extended value list is required:
```
(x, y, z, radius, id, type, parent_id, real_perimeter)
```
where ```x,y,z``` is the center of the cross section, ```radius``` a value that provides the same area as in the cross section and ```real_perimeter``` the perimeter of the cell from file. This extends the existent dataformat by one value.

Maybe we could have a glial cell class and dedicated features for glial cells in the ```features``` module. All features that apply on neurites and neurons can still be applied due to the same positional format.",{},{}
