11213,IssuesEvent,2016-12-05 18:32:52+00:00,16316451,GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python,242750,tseaver,2810941,GoogleCloudPlatform,closed,Support both seconds from epoch and timestamp string,"[{'id': 82126549, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python/labels/bigquery', 'name': 'bigquery', 'color': 'eb6420', 'default': False}, {'id': 77438582, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}]",[],0,"If someone already has a timestamp string, we shouldn't force them to convert it to `datetime.datetime` so that we can in turn [convert that](https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/blob/0c74a599b6aa0a16e21575998e1770182c05e12c/gcloud/bigquery/table.py#L665-L669) into seconds. (Inspired by #1381.)

From [the docs](https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/preparing-data-for-bigquery#datatype)

> TIMESTAMP data types can be described in two ways: UNIX timestamps or calendar datetimes. BigQuery stores TIMESTAMP data internally as a UNIX timestamp with microsecond precision.

so we could allow the user to just pass a string and we ""take their word for it"" that it's a valid datetime. Since `Table.insert_data` returns a list of errors anyhow, we wouldn't have to do much/anything to enforce this.
",{},{}
