12980,IssuesEvent,2017-04-27 06:53:33+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,1418419,kalefranz,6392739,conda,closed,"When lacking permissions to write, clone message should quote prefix.",[],[],0,"When trying to install a new package into a location that the user lacks write permissions (read-only root), conda helpfully suggests cloning the environment into a new location:

```
CondaIOError: IO error: Missing write permissions in: C:\Program Files\Anaconda
#
# You don't appear to have the necessary permissions to install packages
# into the install area 'C:\Program Files\Anaconda'.
# However you can clone this environment into your home directory and
# then make changes to it.
# This may be done using the command:
#
# $ conda create -n my_deathstar --clone=C:\Program Files\Anaconda\envs\deathstar
```
As shown in the example above, this clone path may include spaces. This will be particularly common on Windows, where a global install will result in files written to Program Files, which a non-administrator user will not be able to write to, and contains spaces. Because the command presents a prefix, it should be quoted to guard against this case.

",{},{}
12987,IssuesEvent,2017-05-13 02:18:11+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,1418419,kalefranz,6392739,conda,closed,load saved environment variables in order,"[{'id': 360414999, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/source:community', 'name': 'source:community', 'color': 'c2e0c6', 'default': False}, {'id': 16544530, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/type:bug', 'name': 'type:bug', 'color': 'b60205', 'default': False}]",[],2,"Right now, scripts in `activate.d` are sourced [in whatever order `find` returns them](https://github.com/conda/conda/blob/3c73a234158280e75a44da5705fd3d00f07ac9bc/bin/activate#L95). This order is filesystem-specific and isn't guaranteed stable. This means that packages can't rely on environment variables saved by their requirements.

For example: if package Y requires package X, then environment variables saved by package X may or may not exist when package Y's `activate.d` scripts are sourced. This is surprising because package Y _can_ rely on other assets included in package X.

Reliable order is desirable when a package needs to inspect a dependency's configuration in order to configure itself.

Options might include:
1. Order `activate.d` scripts by the dependency tree. I'm no expert, but this looks difficult given `activate.d`'s current implementation.
2. Order `activate.d` scripts alphabetically (this is [how ipython solves a similar problem](https://ipython.org/ipython-doc/1/config/overview.html#startup-files)). This seems simple to implement.

Either way, this would need a fix for #2767 first.
",{},{}
