13018,IssuesEvent,2018-02-21 19:18:52+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,1418419,kalefranz,6392739,conda,closed,Environment missing from list when created with `conda create -p`,"[{'id': 360414999, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/source:community', 'name': 'source:community', 'color': 'c2e0c6', 'default': False}, {'id': 16544532, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/type:feature', 'name': 'type:feature', 'color': 'e99695', 'default': False}]",[],8,"### Environment

-   conda version: `4.3.14` though I've seen this issue in previous and newer versions as well. All installed through `Anaconda` installers. Tested upto `4.3.21`
-   Python version: `2.7` `3.5` `3.6`. I mean these as the main conda python version
-   Operating System: `Win7`, `Win8`, `Win10`.

### Details

-   Describe what you were trying to get done.

Create and manage a conda environment created in a custom path.

-   What commands did you run to trigger this issue? If you can provide a
    [Minimal, Complete, and Verifiable example](http://stackoverflow.com/help/mcve)
    this will help us understand the issue.

`conda create -p c:\python27 python=2.7`

-   If there was a crash, please include the traceback here.

When running:

```
conda create -p c:\python27 python=2.7
conda env list
```

This returns the following list
```
# conda environments:
#
root                  *  C:\python36
```

But when running
```
conda create -n py35 python=3.5
conda env list
```

This returns
```
# conda environments:
#
py35                     C:\python36\envs\py35
root                  *  C:\python36
```

If I run `activate c:\python27` the correct environment activates with no issue.

Inside of `\.conda\environments.txt` it has
```
c:\python27
C:\python36\envs\py35
```

",{},{}
13019,IssuesEvent,2015-11-29 22:06:52+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,4951214,mountaindust,6392739,conda,opened,Pyplot crashes in windows 10 powershell,[],[],0,"I'm running Python 3.5.0, Anaconda 2.4.0 (64-bit) on Windows 10. All packages are up to date as of 11/29/2015 4:55pm EST.

To reproduce:
1. Open Windows PowerShell.
2. Start ipython
3. Enter: ""import matplotlib.pyplot as plt"". A message appears: ""Qt: Untested Windows version 10.0 detected!
4. Enter: ""plt.plot([1,2,3]). (Out line shows a matplotlib.lines.Line2D object)
5. Enter: ""plt.show()"". A window appears with the plot as expected. However, wait a few seconds (less than a minute typically), and a popup window will appear saying that Python has stopped responding. Ipython then crashes, closing the plot window and dumping you back to the command prompt.

This problem is NOT reproduced using the Anaconda Prompt or IPython from the start menu. When a regular command prompt is used, you get the same problem.",{},{}
