13125,IssuesEvent,2017-04-12 17:48:38+00:00,16557526,pysam-developers/pysam,12798364,Osiris1975,6598771,pysam-developers,opened,Can pysam return raw read counts instead of alignments?,[],[],0,"I am looking for a way to get raw count of mapped + unmapped reads from a bam file. It seems to me idxstats and pysam.count both return alignments, not raw reads. If I take a bam file and perform 
samtools view file.bam | cut -f 1 | sort -u > foo | wc -l at terminal, I get a very different number than what pysam.count provides since reads can align to multiple places. So does pysam have a built-in version of what I've done at terminal?",{},{}
13128,IssuesEvent,2017-09-30 22:32:30+00:00,16557526,pysam-developers/pysam,1105137,nieder,6598771,pysam-developers,opened,Are modules libraries or plugins?,[],[],0,"Are the modules in site-packages/pysam/*.so supposed to be libraries linked to at buildtime or plugins loaded at runtime?

On macOS, they're named like libcalignedsegment.so, but they're created as linkable dylibs (`-dynamiclib`). If they're libraries other programs are supposed to link to at runtime, they should end with a `.dylib` extension. If they're runtime plugins, they should not use `-dynamiclib`, `-rpath`, `-install-name`, etc., as defined in cy_build.py.

Since other pysam modules link to some of these modules (eg libcsamfile.so links to libchtslib.so), then it looks like they're meant to be dynamic libraries (you can't link to a plugin), and should therefore have a .dylib extension.",{},{}
