13457,IssuesEvent,2017-11-03 21:06:22+00:00,39039065,Azure/azure-storage-python,26559128,zezha-msft,6844498,Azure,closed,Retry callback should provide exception context,"[{'id': 235876947, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-storage-python/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}]",[],3,"The retry handling logic should provide the **unwrapped** exception context (i.e., the exception that `AzureException` wraps) to the `retry_callback()`. Please see the [affected code](https://github.com/Azure/azure-storage-python/blob/master/azure-storage-common/azure/storage/common/storageclient.py#L343).

There does not seem to be a good reason to suppress this information from custom retry handlers and obfuscates why a retry is being called (and thus why an exception was raised for the request). Simply discerning that a `context.response` of `None` as [**always** needing a retry is arbitrary](https://github.com/Azure/azure-storage-python/blob/master/azure-storage-common/azure/storage/common/retry.py#L60-L65) and does not apply to all situations. For example, a connection fault (i.e., Exception) from the lower layer urllib3 of `[Errno -2] Name or service not known` should not be retried, but will always be retried with no way to change this behavior without providing a `try/except` around the actual storage SDK call itself. Doing so would defeat the purpose of custom retry handlers wrapping this type of functionality.

The proposal is to either add the exception context on the `RetryContext` or add an optional parameter to the `retry_callback` function. The former would be a cleaner approach.",{},{}
