13605,IssuesEvent,2017-11-17 17:05:52+00:00,13258039,aio-libs/aiohttp,8330436,germn,7049303,aio-libs,opened,ClientSession request can't be cancelled without RuntimeError sometimes,[],[],0,"## Code to reproduce:
```
import asyncio
import aiohttp
from contextlib import suppress


async def request(url):
    async with aiohttp.ClientSession() as session:
        async with session.get(url) as resp:
            return await resp.text()


async def main(url):
    task = asyncio.ensure_future(request(url))

    await asyncio.sleep(0.001)

    task.cancel()
    with suppress(asyncio.CancelledError):
        await task

    print('done')


loop = asyncio.get_event_loop()
try:
    url = 'http://httpbin.org/delay/1'
    # url = 'http://broken'

    loop.run_until_complete(main(url))
    loop.run_until_complete(loop.shutdown_asyncgens())
finally:
    loop.close()
```

## Actual behaviour

`RuntimeError: Event loop is closed`

Msg for normal url:
`exception calling callback for <Future at 0x1ad769f6f60 state=finished returned list>`

Msg for broken url:
`exception calling callback for <Future at 0x2cecb9dd2b0 state=finished raised gaierror>`

## Expected behaviour

We should be able to cancel request without unexpected exceptions/messages.

I discovered behavior trying to answer [this](https://stackoverflow.com/q/47353461/1113207) question. 

Google showes two year old [issue](https://github.com/aio-libs/aiohttp/issues/441) with same problem. Workaround [mentioned there](https://github.com/aio-libs/aiohttp/issues/441#issuecomment-130678262) doesn't work and anyway is not a fix.

## Your environment

Windows 10, Python 3.6.2, aiohttp==2.3.3",{},{}
