13887,IssuesEvent,2018-04-30 22:53:57+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,3019665,jakirkham,7388996,jupyter,opened,Activating conda environments before using their Python as a kernel,[],[],0,"Currently a user can install a new kernel from a `conda` environment by doing something like this.

```bash
$ conda activate my_py_env
$ python -m ipykernel install --prefix ""${CONDA_PREFIX}""
```

This works fine for most cases. However if you need the environment activated when the Jupyter Notebook opens a new kernel, this won't work.

One naive option would be to write a shell wrapper script that behaves like a `python` executable and handles the activation step before doing whatever the user wants with `python`. Here's a quick one that I tried. More performant ones can created with [`exec-wrappers`]( https://github.com/gqmelo/exec-wrappers ).

```bash
#!/bin/bash

set -e

conda deactivate || true
set -a
. /opt/conda/etc/profile.d/conda.sh
conda activate my_py_env
set +a

exec ""$CONDA_PYTHON_EXE"" ""$@""
```

If you play with this script on the command line, it has the behavior one would expect. Namely the environment is activated, `conda` can recognize what environment it should use. Any package activation scripts have run and work as expected.

However as soon as this is run through `ipykernel install`, it points back to the `python` interpreter in the `conda` environment. Admittedly this is probably from checking `sys.executable` and adding to kernel spec. One could go back and edit the kernel spec to fix this. Alternatively an `--exe` option could be given to `ipykernel install` to override the executable used (maybe a footgun?). Maybe there is a better option? Then again this was a hacky attempt to get activation to work. So optimizing for it may not make sense.

There are things like [`jupyter_environment_kernels`]( https://github.com/Cadair/jupyter_environment_kernels ), which will actually activate the environment. ( https://github.com/Cadair/jupyter_environment_kernels/pull/29 ) In theory, tools like [`nb_conda_kernels`]( https://github.com/Anaconda-Platform/nb_conda_kernels ) would also work here, but that doesn't appear to be the case. ( https://github.com/Anaconda-Platform/nb_conda_kernels/issues/54 ) ( https://github.com/Anaconda-Platform/nb_conda_kernels/issues/19 ) ( https://github.com/Anaconda-Platform/nb_conda_kernels/issues/42 )

Though it would be nice to have some proper, simple activation support in Jupyter Notebook kernels outright.",{},{}
