14563,IssuesEvent,2015-02-17 11:56:22+00:00,1151051,django-oscar/django-oscar,509427,maikhoepfel,9057806,django-oscar,opened,Category handling overhaul bucket,[],[],0,"At my current job, we're running into some issues with category handling. I get some time to improve the state of things in Oscar.

Goals:
- Easily allow editing slugs independently of names. slugs are important for SEO and might need to match legacy URLs, so the auto-generating of slugs should be an optional step. (#561)
- Address MySQL size limits (#1119). I haven't thought it through just yet, but I think removing the ``full_slug``/full name denormalization is the way to go, as it nicely simplifies the slug updating process. Any performance issues can nicely be handled with a cache.

I'll attempt to watch out for:
- not increasing query counts considerably
- not breaking existing URLs

Bonus goals:
- Ensure that it's easy to translate categories.
- Ensure that it's easy to display them alphabetically.
- Ensure that it's easy to not display categories without products.",{},{}
14580,IssuesEvent,2018-07-12 21:32:05+00:00,26784827,dotnet/core,9010698,weshaggard,9141961,dotnet,closed,"""Multiple assemblies with equivalent identity have been imported"" when importing more than one NuGet package referencing NuGet.Build.Packaging",[],[],3,"I came across this issue where a ASP.NET Core application would fail to build when installing certain NuGet packages with a bunch of these errors:

`/Users/user/projects/BugReport/Broken/CSC: Error CS1703: Multiple assemblies with equivalent identity have been imported: '/Users/user/.nuget/packages/breakmetwo/0.0.1/lib/netstandard2.0/System.Threading.Tasks.Parallel.dll' and '/Users/user/.nuget/packages/microsoft.netcore.app/2.0.0/ref/netcoreapp2.0/System.Threading.Tasks.Parallel.dll'. Remove one of the duplicate references. (CS1703) (Broken)`

`/Users/user/projects/BugReport/Broken/CSC: Error CS1703: Multiple assemblies with equivalent identity have been imported: '/Users/user/.nuget/packages/breakmetwo/0.0.1/lib/netstandard2.0/System.Runtime.Serialization.Json.dll' and '/Users/user/.nuget/packages/microsoft.netcore.app/2.0.0/ref/netcoreapp2.0/System.Runtime.Serialization.Json.dll'. Remove one of the duplicate references. (CS1703) (Broken)`

`/Users/user/projects/BugReport/Broken/Controllers/UselessController.cs(44,44): Error CS0731: The type forwarder for type 'System.Object' in assembly 'System.Runtime' causes a cycle (CS0731) (Broken)`

The NuGet packages are created in house. The NuGet packages are hosted on a shared drive. After a lot of hours of researching and troubleshooting this, I found out that NuGet packages created of projects referencing NuGet.Build.Packaging were causing those errors. The NuGet packages were created referencing NuGet.Build.Packaging 0.2.0 and also 0.2.2, both producing the same outcome.

These errors only showed up when more than one NuGet package references NuGet.Build.Packaging. The attached project contains two .NETStandard libraries (BreakMeOne and BreakMeTwo) referencing NuGet.Build.Packaging. If only one of either of those libraries is imported, the project builds fine. When the second library is imported, the build fails. If I regenerate either of the packages without the reference to NuGet.Build.Packaging, the project builds fine.

This is the output of dotnet --info of the machine where the packages were created:

```
$ dotnet --info
.NET Command Line Tools (2.1.4)

Product Information:
 Version:            2.1.4
 Commit SHA-1 hash:  5e8add2190

Runtime Environment:
 OS Name:     Mac OS X
