15532,IssuesEvent,2016-03-05 02:51:17+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,3085284,NikolajBjorner,11668813,Z3Prover,closed,`is_irrational_algebraic_numeral` et al. may receive null arguments,[],[],3,"Here is a simple demonstration of what could trigger this bug
```
(set-option :numeral-as-real true)
(declare-const x Real)

(simplify (acos (/ 2)))
```

I would fix this but I am not sure if the issue should be tackled at the `simplify_cmd` level or if the arithmetic utility functions should be changed to return an errno. Much of the simplification code receives malformed input happily, so fixing this somewhat minor bug could be a fairly large undertaking unless z3 just panics when processing empty literals (which would probably be best anyway)
",{},{}
15537,IssuesEvent,2016-01-08 04:54:24+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,3085284,NikolajBjorner,11668813,Z3Prover,closed,Z3 internals: simulating (declare-const) from inside a theory plugin,[],[],8,"One of the reduction steps in the theory plugin (for strings) I'm working on involves creating a fresh string variable and then asserting some facts about it. I couldn't find any other theory plugins that need to do something like this, so I guessed that the best approach would be to simulate what `smt2parser` does when it encounters a `(declare-const)` expression. To this end I have the following code:

```
app * theory_str::mk_str_var(std::string name) {
	context & ctx = get_context();
	ast_manager & m = get_manager();

	sort * string_sort = m.mk_sort(m_strutil.get_family_id(), STRING_SORT);
	char * new_buffer = alloc_svect(char, name.length() + 1);
	strcpy(new_buffer, name.c_str());
	symbol sym(new_buffer);

	app * a = m.mk_const(m.mk_const_decl(sym, string_sort));

	ctx.internalize(a, false);
	SASSERT(ctx.get_enode(a) != NULL);
	SASSERT(ctx.e_internalized(a));
	m_basicstr_axiom_todo.push_back(ctx.get_enode(a));

        // some internal stuff I have to keep track of
	variable_set.insert(a);
	internal_variable_set.insert(a);
	track_variable_scope(a);

	return a;
}
```

It seems that this method works sometimes and fails other times. In particular, in one test case I'm working with, I create a temporary variable and make some assertions with it, then the solver pops the context (deallocating that variable in the process), and then later I create a second temporary variable (with a different name). The first variable successfully has the assertions applied; the second one fails the assertion `get_id() >= c_first_decl_id` in `ast/ast.h:547`. This is very strange, and inspecting the object in the debugger seems to suggest that some of its fields don't point to valid memory.

It's definitely not the case that the fresh variable goes out of context before I try to use it. The context doesn't push or pop before this assertion failure; the variable is created and then immediately used in the same method without returning control to the solver.

If it matters, I'm doing all of this inside `final_check_eh()`.

The other strange factor is that code similar to this worked in a previous version of this string solver (Z3str2, built against Z3 4.1.1) with the code:

```
Z3_ast mk_var(Z3_context ctx, const char * name, Z3_sort ty) {
  Z3_symbol s = Z3_mk_string_symbol(ctx, name);
  return Z3_mk_const(ctx, s, ty);
}
```

and `Z3_mk_const()` doing almost exactly what I'm doing here except also calling the function `save_ast_trail()` which I cannot seem to access from the new API.

I would appreciate any assistance you can provide with respect to how to generate fresh theory variables / constants from inside my theory plugin.",{},{}
15540,IssuesEvent,2016-05-13 13:01:16+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,3164095,codesn1,11668813,Z3Prover,opened,Statement and its complement both satisfyable,[],[],0,"I found that if you compare the value of bvmul with its arguments extended and the value of brmul with itself extended, the resulting formula is always satisfyable. For example:

`(= (bvmul ((_ sign_extend 7) %X) ((_ sign_extend 7) C1)) ((_ sign_extend 7) (bvmul %X C1)))`

Is satisfyable if asserted, but so is:

`(not (= (bvmul ((_ sign_extend 7) %X) ((_ sign_extend 7) C1)) ((_ sign_extend 7) (bvmul %X C1))))`

I've attached example *.smt2 files, one with signed bitvectors and one with unsigned: [examples.zip](https://github.com/Z3Prover/z3/files/263288/examples.zip)

Here's the output of --version:

```
$ ./z3 --version
Z3 version 4.4.1
```

And here's the command line I was using to solve the *.smt2 file (running on Ubuntu 14.04):

`$ ./z3 example1.smt2`",{},{}
