15844,IssuesEvent,2018-05-28 06:29:44+00:00,40328394,angr/angr,2498805,rhelmot,12520807,angr,opened,Filesystem refactor is not finished,[],[],0,"while trying to figure out how to implement stat once and for all, I realized that I fucked up the filesystem refactor. namely, while running a linux guest program, it's very important that every file descriptor always correspond to exactly one file. This means we have to implement the console by having the duplexing happen not at the file descriptor level but at the SimFile level, which I'm very much unhappy with. This would, however, mesh with the [linux API for file objects](https://www.tldp.org/LDP/lkmpg/2.4/html/c577.htm).

However, two hours of wading through the kernel source have not provided me with any further pointers as to what the abstractions ought to be from here. Ideally, SimFile would be a totally opaque interface and we could all go home happy but as I learned during wip/new_files, wayyyyyy too much code tries to poke and prod at SimFile directly in the midst of execution.

The tentative game plan is:

- Keep the duplex fd around since it is a useful tool if anyone wants to use it, but don't ever automatically use it
- SimFileDescriptor holds a SimFile, a position, a mode, and the name it was originally opened as (e.g. `readlink(/proc/self/fd/n)`
- SimFileBase adds a `stat` method
- Add a SimFileDuplex which itself holds two SimFiles...?
- Store one of these as /dev/tty in the posix mount
- Get rid of `read_storage` and `write_storage`, any code which needs one specifically (scanf mostly iirc) should detect SimFileDuplex and drill into it manually
- if I have to spend another two weeks debugging mechaphish I'm going to stab someone

Additionally, some TODOs I had floating around which were never fully resolved, unrelated to the above stat-motivated mess:

- Directories need to be represented in SimFilesystem somehow. Current tendency is to just have another class that can exist in `state.fs._files`, with all its ""children"" just being present in the dict as well but with a longer path, and then having utility methods for getting the elements under a given directory.
- Directory file descriptors are a whole different can of worms, but they do need consideration. The basic version can just be to have another subclass of SimFileDescriptorBase which tells you to fuck off if you call anything other than directory-related methods on it.
- Sockets at one point had serious consideration in the design of the posix plugin, but as far as I can tell nobody is using them anymore. I tried to implement a good system for dealing with sockets but never actually tested it, either to make sure it actually worked or to make sure the interfaces are sufficient.
- Implement dup and friends
- Implement a super-lightweight `state.fs` plugin that has some ability to reason about symbolic filepaths.",{},{}
