16975,IssuesEvent,2018-06-25 07:21:47+00:00,63484632,facebookresearch/fastText,28563421,sribharghava,16943930,facebookresearch,opened,Supervised Model accuracy not consistent over different training runs,[],[],0,"Thanks for this library! We're using fastText as one of our classification methods internally and it fits perfectly in our environment, thanks to your python wrapper, but it fails some of the test cases that we have internally out of which one seems very intriguing; details below.

For the binary classification task, we have a very tiny dataset with 7 samples; 3 +ve and 4 -ve. 
When we tried hyperparameter optimization with 'cv' as '3' on this dataset with `epoch: [0, 50] and lr: [0, 0.5]` as the param grid, fasttext always returned epoch as 0 and lr as 0 as its best params! 
And when we tried with a slightly different configuration of `epcoh: [1, 50] lr: [01, 0.5]`; the param choosing has become random; we get epoch 1 as best parameter sometimes and epoch 50 sometimes.    
The only reason that I could think of for this kind of behaviour is the random initialisation of weights in some of the internal layers! But the scores returned in the first case i.e. `epoch: [0, 50] and lr: [0, 0.5]` are always same which contradicts my assumption. Please throw some light on this.

Details of the environment:
We're using the up-to-date python wrapper that is on your master branch.  

The test dataset is as follows:
['good', '+ve'], ['awesome movie', '+ve'], ['awesome song', '+ve'], ['terrible', '-ve'], ['bad', '-ve'], ['horrible', '-ve'], ['terribly horrible movie', '-ve']]

We are using the train_supervised API with all the default params.",{},{}
