17174,IssuesEvent,2017-08-31 16:26:08+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,9640520,rleigh-codelibre,17565521,pybind,closed,Segfault with map_caster and GCC 4.8,[],[],6,"## Issue description

Testing with v2.1.1. When wrapping a shared library which contains methods returning a reference to a map, the wrapper segfaults when trying to use the map.  This occurs with GCC 4.8.5 on CentOS7 and is independent of the Python version used.  If I use GCC 5.3.1 from devtoolset-4, it works just fine.  I've tried with Python 2.6.5, 2.7.13 and 3.5.1, and it works in all cases with GCC 5.3.1 and fails in all cases with GCC 4.8.5.

It looks like the fault is in map_caster (see the segfault and backtrace below).

I have tested building the shared library and pybind11 wrapper with different GCC versions:

shlib | wrapper | result
-------|------------|--------
4.8.5 | 4.8.4 | FAIL
4.8.5 | 5.3.1 | FAIL
5.3.1 | 4.8.4 | FAIL
5.3.1 | 5.3.1 | PASS

It's quite likely there's something odd happening specifically with GCC 4.8, but I'm unsure if pybind11 is also doing something to trigger this condition, which might make it possible to work around the problem.  Or it might be a subtle issue inside map_caster.

## Reproducible example code

I've created a small reduced testcase here: https://github.com/rleigh-codelibre/test-pybind11 comprising a small shared library with the method returning the map, plus the pybind11 wrapper and unit test.  The steps to build and test are shown below, along with the output I get in a plain CentOS 7 VM.

