	/lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2 (0x0000563626045000)
```

**Attempting to run `run_test.py`:**

    $ ./run_test.py 
    ( just hangs indefinitely... )

**Attempting to run `run_test.py` through python:** (note: might be nice to add a hash-bang to `run_test.py`)

    $ python ./run_test.py 
    Syntax: run_test.py [--relaxed] <test name>

**Attempt to run `example1.py` through `run_test.py`:** 

    $ python ./run_test.py ./example1.py

>```
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""./run_test.py"", line 58, in <module>
    stderr=subprocess.STDOUT)
  File ""/usr/lib/python2.7/subprocess.py"", line 573, in check_output
    raise CalledProcessError(retcode, cmd, output=output)
subprocess.CalledProcessError: Command '['/usr/bin/python', './example1.py.py']' returned non-zero exit status 2
```

**Attempt to run `example1` through `run_test.py`:** 

    $ python ./run_test.py ./example1

>```
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""./run_test.py"", line 58, in <module>
    stderr=subprocess.STDOUT)
  File ""/usr/lib/python2.7/subprocess.py"", line 573, in check_output
    raise CalledProcessError(retcode, cmd, output=output)
subprocess.CalledProcessError: Command '['/usr/bin/python', './example1.py']' returned non-zero exit status 2
```

So this begs the question - how do I run the tests, individually, from the command line?",{},{}
