17191,IssuesEvent,2016-04-22 21:13:19+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,211955,pschella,17565521,pybind,opened,Convenience functions for casting between PyObject and underlying smart pointer,[],[],0,"When integrating pybind11 with other Python wrapper tools it is often necessary to extract smart pointers from pybind11 wrapped objects or conversely construct a `pybind11::object` from a smart pointer. For instance the following swig typemaps will allow swig wrapped functions to accept and return pybind11 wrapped `MyType` objects (backed by a `shared_ptr`).

    %typemap(out) std::shared_ptr<MyType> {
        /* Use a pybind11 typecaster to create a PyObject from a shared_ptr<MyType> */
        pybind11::detail::type_caster<std::shared_ptr<MyType>> caster;
        pybind11::handle out = caster.cast($1, pybind11::return_value_policy::take_ownership, pybind11::handle());
        $result = out.ptr();
    }

    %typemap(in) std::shared_ptr<MyType> {
        /* First make a pybind11 object handler around the PyObject *
         * Then, cast it to a shared_ptr<MyType> using the pybind11 caster. */
        pybind11::object p{$input, true};
        try {
            std::shared_ptr<MyType> ptr(p.cast<std::shared_ptr<MyType>>());
            $1 = ptr;
        } catch(...) {
            PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError, ""could not cast to shared_ptr<MyType>"");
            return nullptr;
        }
    }

But this exposes quite a bit of the internals of pybind11 (namely the typecaster). It would be nice if pybind11 included a few convenience functions to do this.",{},{}
17197,IssuesEvent,2017-06-23 14:52:10+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,6416159,molpopgen,17565521,pybind,opened,Eventual collisions between opaque STL containers,[],[],0,"After some chatting on gitter, @jagerman suggested that I raise an issue here, mostly so that it can be kept track of.

This is related to #439, but has more to do with what happens in the long run when more and more packages are developed using pybind11.

Currently,  opaque STL containers are most often generated with a combo of the `PYBIND11_MAKE_OPAQUE` macro and a call to `py::bind_vector`.

If two different modules by different developers generate the same opaque containers, an import error occurs if both modules are used together.  One simple solution is to wrap the binding in try/catch blocks as shown here: https://github.com/molpopgen/opaque_test.  (That example uses ccpimport to compile the code.)

However, the try/catch solution is imperfect: the name seed on the Python side depends on the import order.  Further, there is the deeper problem that `py::bind_vector` may optionally be invoked with `py::buffer_protocol()` and that the class type returned may be further augmented via `.defs` in the usual way.  The possible result then is that both the name and features/behavior depend on import order, which seems less than ideal.

The gitter discussion ended with the agreement that a solution is needed and that it is not clear what that solution should look like.
",{},{}
