17857,IssuesEvent,2018-08-16 00:34:10+00:00,72477752,pulumi/pulumi,1409156,hausdorff,21992475,pulumi,opened,`pulumi new` cancel is a bit awkward,[],"[{'login': 'justinvp', 'id': 710598, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjcxMDU5OA==', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars3.githubusercontent.com/u/710598?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/justinvp', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/justinvp', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/justinvp/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/justinvp/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/justinvp/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/justinvp/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/justinvp/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/justinvp/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/justinvp/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/justinvp/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/justinvp/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",0,"When you do something like:

```sh
pulumi new https://github.com/pulumi/templates/tree/justin/k8s/kubernetes-typescript
```

and then cancel partway through, the CLI does not seem to clean up after itself. In particular, the directory contains a bunch of files, and the stack may or may not have been created, depending on how far you get.

The major pain of this is that if you try to re-run the command, you are not in charge of deleting all the stuff. I believe that what we really want to do is to delete this proactively on behalf of the user if we don't make it completely through init. (This is essentially what we did in ksonnet and believe me when I say it saved us so much heartache.)",{},{}
17859,IssuesEvent,2018-08-13 20:18:04+00:00,72477752,pulumi/pulumi,9602953,ellismg,21992475,pulumi,closed,Issue an informative message on `pulumi` invocations with out-of-date `pulumi` CLI,[],"[{'login': 'ellismg', 'id': 9602953, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjk2MDI5NTM=', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars0.githubusercontent.com/u/9602953?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ellismg', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/ellismg', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ellismg/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ellismg/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ellismg/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ellismg/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ellismg/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ellismg/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ellismg/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ellismg/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ellismg/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",0,"We are releasing new `pulumi` CLI drops regularly, and adding features which are needed to take advantage of the latest libraries and features in the service.  To ensure that users by default get the best experience, we should post an info message as part of `pulumi` CLI invocations (or perhaps some specific subset of commands) when the CLI being used is out of date.  We may initially want to be reasonably quick to mark builds as ""out of date"" while we are making meaningful improvements in each release, and then slow down as things stabilize further.",{},{}
17865,IssuesEvent,2018-08-08 20:46:06+00:00,72477752,pulumi/pulumi,1871912,swgillespie,21992475,pulumi,closed,Fix refresh to work with parallelism,"[{'id': 986163784, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw5ODYxNjM3ODQ=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pulumi/pulumi/labels/kubernetes/inner-dev-loop', 'name': 'kubernetes/inner-dev-loop', 'color': 'b913d3', 'default': False}]","[{'login': 'swgillespie', 'id': 1871912, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjE4NzE5MTI=', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars2.githubusercontent.com/u/1871912?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/swgillespie', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/swgillespie/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",0,"Today's implementation of `refresh` sends source events eagerly to the engine. The engine requires that source events arrive in dependency order. However, the refresh source does not prevent dependent resources from being processed by the engine at the same time, which can result in nondeterministic snapshot validation errors. 

cc @hausdorff @pgavlin ",{},{}
